<meta name=3D"DC.Description" content=3D"A modular inverse of an integer b =
(modulo m) is the integer b^(-1) such that  bb^(-1)=3D1 (mod m).   A modula=
r inverse can be computed in the Wolfram Language using ModularInverse[b, m=
] or PowerMod[b, -1, m]. Every nonzero integer b has an inverse (modulo p) =
for p a prime and b not a multiple of p. For example, the modular inverses =
of 1, 2, 3, and 4 (mod 5) are 1, 3, 2, and 4. If m is not prime, then not e=
very nonzero integer b has a modular inverse. In fact, a nonzero integer b =
has a modular...">
