<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Modular Inverse</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/NumberTheory/ModularInve=
rse.nb" download=3D"ModularInverse.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27"=
 alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
A modular inverse of an integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i=
mages/equations/ModularInverse/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" =
alt=3D"b"> (modulo <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/ModularInverse/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:=
100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">) is=
 the integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mod=
ularInverse/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"24" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b^(-1)"> such=
 that
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/ModularInverse/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequati=
on" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"124" hei=
ght=3D"20" alt=3D" bb^(-1)=3D1 (mod m). "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
A modular inverse can be computed in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/=
language/">Wolfram Language</a> using <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfr=
am.com/language/ref/ModularInverse.html">ModularInverse</a></tt>[<i>b</i>,
 <i>m</i>] or <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Powe=
rMod.html">PowerMod</a></tt>[<i>b</i>,
 <tt>-1</tt>, <i>m</i>].
</p>
<p>
Every nonzero integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/ModularInverse/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heig=
ht:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b">
 has an inverse (modulo <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/ModularInverse/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-he=
ight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p"=
>)
 for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInve=
rse/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p">
 a prime and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mod=
ularInverse/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b">
 not a multiple of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/ModularInverse/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:=
100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"p">.
 For example, the modular inverses of 1, 2, 3, and 4 (mod 5) are 1, 3, 2, a=
nd 4.
</p>
<p>
If <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInvers=
e/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">
 is not prime, then not every nonzero integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlinef=
ormula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" h=
eight=3D"21" alt=3D"b"> has a modular inverse. In fact, a nonzero integer <=
img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/In=
line11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%=
" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b"> has a modular inverse m=
odulo <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInv=
erse/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m"> <a href=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/Iff.html">iff</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" hei=
ght=3D"21" alt=3D"b"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/ModularInverse/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"m"> are <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RelativelyPrime.html">rel=
atively prime</a>.
 For example, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mo=
dularInverse/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"54" height=3D"21" alt=3D"1^(-1)=3D1"=
>
 (mod 4) and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mod=
ularInverse/Inline16.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"54" height=3D"21" alt=3D"3^(-1)=3D3">
 (mod 4), but 2 does not have a modular inverse.
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/ModularInverse/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequati=
on" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"57" heig=
ht=3D"141" alt=3D" 1=20
12=20
103=20
1324=20
10005=20
145236  "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
The triangle above (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A102057">A102057</a>) g=
ives modular inverses of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/ModularInverse/Inline17.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b=
">
 (mod <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInv=
erse/Inline18.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">)
 for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInve=
rse/Inline19.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b=3D1">,
 2, ..., <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Modular=
Inverse/Inline20.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"41" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m-1">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInve=
rse/Inline21.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m=3D2">,
 3, .... 0 indicates that no modular inverse exists.
</p>
<p>
If <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInvers=
e/Inline22.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInve=
rse/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">
 are relatively prime, there exist integers <img src=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" hei=
ght=3D"21" alt=3D"x"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/ModularInverse/Inline25.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"=
y"> such that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mo=
dularInverse/Inline26.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"97" height=3D"21" alt=3D"bx+my=3D1">=
, and such integers may be found using the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/EuclideanAlgorithm.html">Euclidean
 algorithm</a>. Considering this equation modulo <img src=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline27.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"1=
3" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">, it follows that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline28.svg" class=3D"inlinefo=
rmula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"50" h=
eight=3D"21" alt=3D"bx=3D1">; i.e., <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/images/equations/ModularInverse/Inline29.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"115" height=3D=
"21" alt=3D"x=3Db^(-1) (mod m)">.
</p>
<p>
If <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInvers=
e/Inline30.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularInve=
rse/Inline31.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"m">
 are relatively prime, then <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Eulers=
TotientTheorem.html">Euler's totient theorem</a>
 states that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Mod=
ularInverse/Inline32.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"128" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b^(phi(m))=
=3D1 (mod m)">,
 where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ModularIn=
verse/Inline33.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"36" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi(m)">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TotientFunction.html">toti=
ent function</a>. Hence, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/ModularInverse/Inline34.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"157" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"b^(-1)=3Db^(phi(m)-1) (mod m)">.
</p>
